WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.932 --> 00:00:03.750
JON WILEY: Hi everybody.

00:00:03.750 --> 00:00:04.250
Welcome.

00:00:10.630 --> 00:00:13.960
So during the keynote
you heard a little bit

00:00:13.960 --> 00:00:17.350
about material
design, and we hope

00:00:17.350 --> 00:00:20.967
to give you a little bit
more detail about that today

00:00:20.967 --> 00:00:22.675
and in the sessions
that follow tomorrow.

00:00:24.852 --> 00:00:26.560
But first I want to
tell you a little bit

00:00:26.560 --> 00:00:32.100
about our inspiration
around material design.

00:00:32.100 --> 00:00:34.300
Every object in this
room owes its origin

00:00:34.300 --> 00:00:37.400
to a few people throughout
the millennia who

00:00:37.400 --> 00:00:40.040
paid careful attention
to their environment.

00:00:40.040 --> 00:00:41.884
They sought out the
very best materials,

00:00:41.884 --> 00:00:43.300
and they learned
their properties.

00:00:43.300 --> 00:00:47.640
And they used this
knowledge to make things.

00:00:47.640 --> 00:00:52.520
And when you consider
making things, the design

00:00:52.520 --> 00:00:54.600
and the manufacture
of things, we

00:00:54.600 --> 00:00:58.670
inherit thousands of
years of expertise.

00:00:58.670 --> 00:01:02.360
In contrast, relatively,
software design

00:01:02.360 --> 00:01:03.713
is just getting started.

00:01:03.713 --> 00:01:05.379
Much of interface
design concerns itself

00:01:05.379 --> 00:01:06.730
with what people see.

00:01:06.730 --> 00:01:09.290
But with modern high
resolution displays

00:01:09.290 --> 00:01:11.750
coupled with the ability
to physically interact

00:01:11.750 --> 00:01:15.794
with the software your
expectations are much greater.

00:01:15.794 --> 00:01:17.960
In fact, there's thousands
of years of expectations.

00:01:20.570 --> 00:01:25.865
And so we took a step back.

00:01:25.865 --> 00:01:27.240
We looked at all
of this software

00:01:27.240 --> 00:01:30.040
and we asked what
is this made of?

00:01:30.040 --> 00:01:32.710
We challenged ourselves
to define the underlying

00:01:32.710 --> 00:01:36.510
physics of our interfaces, and
craft a visual language which

00:01:36.510 --> 00:01:39.817
unifies the classic
concepts of good design

00:01:39.817 --> 00:01:41.400
with a solid
understanding of the most

00:01:41.400 --> 00:01:44.490
fundamental physical properties.

00:01:44.490 --> 00:01:47.060
At first we thought
like designers.

00:01:47.060 --> 00:01:48.650
How should it appear?

00:01:48.650 --> 00:01:51.140
How should it look?

00:01:51.140 --> 00:01:54.140
But then we thought
like scientists.

00:01:54.140 --> 00:01:57.590
Why does it behave this way?

00:01:57.590 --> 00:02:01.630
And after many experiments
and many observations

00:02:01.630 --> 00:02:05.390
we wrote down everything
that we'd learned.

00:02:05.390 --> 00:02:07.640
These are our
material principles.

00:02:18.645 --> 00:02:19.520
MATIAS DUARTE: Hello.

00:02:19.520 --> 00:02:22.270
In Android 4.0,
Ice Cream Sandwich,

00:02:22.270 --> 00:02:26.460
we introduced a typographic
magazines style UI,

00:02:26.460 --> 00:02:29.170
and a lot of people liked it.

00:02:29.170 --> 00:02:32.310
We were pretty happy with it.

00:02:32.310 --> 00:02:37.070
But design is
continually evolving.

00:02:37.070 --> 00:02:39.400
Users are getting
more sophisticated.

00:02:39.400 --> 00:02:42.210
The design landscape
is more sophisticated.

00:02:42.210 --> 00:02:45.536
In particular, motion has
become incredibly important

00:02:45.536 --> 00:02:46.535
over the last few years.

00:02:50.138 --> 00:02:55.170
We wanted something
that was taking

00:02:55.170 --> 00:03:00.360
the very best of
graphic design clarity,

00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:03.170
and the innovations
in motion graphics,

00:03:03.170 --> 00:03:07.880
and motion communication,
but that still

00:03:07.880 --> 00:03:12.980
taped into those elements of
tangibility, of physicality

00:03:12.980 --> 00:03:16.230
that industrial
designers themselves use.

00:03:19.840 --> 00:03:24.450
So this led us to a question
of how do we do this?

00:03:24.450 --> 00:03:28.230
And the very first
principle in material design

00:03:28.230 --> 00:03:33.080
is metaphor, which
seems a little random.

00:03:33.080 --> 00:03:34.590
Why metaphor?

00:03:34.590 --> 00:03:38.720
Metaphor is basically a
very, very short story.

00:03:38.720 --> 00:03:42.450
And like stories, metaphors are
really powerful because they

00:03:42.450 --> 00:03:45.700
are deep and dense in meaning.

00:03:45.700 --> 00:03:49.685
They communicate more richly
than verbal language can.

00:03:52.450 --> 00:03:54.500
If I'm writing a play
or if I'm telling you

00:03:54.500 --> 00:03:56.705
about a character or
a person in real life,

00:03:56.705 --> 00:04:01.100
if I say she was a
hurricane, I don't

00:04:01.100 --> 00:04:04.580
have to tell you about
her force of will

00:04:04.580 --> 00:04:06.330
or her indomitable spirit.

00:04:06.330 --> 00:04:10.120
I don't have to tell an
actor that averting her gaze

00:04:10.120 --> 00:04:12.060
would be inappropriate.

00:04:12.060 --> 00:04:15.570
The metaphor is a form
of knowledge transfer

00:04:15.570 --> 00:04:17.790
that depends on
shared experience.

00:04:17.790 --> 00:04:21.650
And in fact, this capacity
to transfer knowledge

00:04:21.650 --> 00:04:23.940
and to transfer learning
is one of the things

00:04:23.940 --> 00:04:28.550
that defines humanity, and,
in fact, defines intelligence.

00:04:28.550 --> 00:04:35.560
So for us the idea of metaphor
is a backstory for the design.

00:04:35.560 --> 00:04:37.910
It unifies and
grounds the design,

00:04:37.910 --> 00:04:39.840
and it has two functions.

00:04:39.840 --> 00:04:42.760
It works for our audience.

00:04:42.760 --> 00:04:46.770
We want to present a metaphor
that they can understand,

00:04:46.770 --> 00:04:52.120
that they can connect with,
that they can use to move faster

00:04:52.120 --> 00:04:54.780
into understanding
how to use things.

00:04:54.780 --> 00:04:57.740
But it's also a
metaphor for ourselves,

00:04:57.740 --> 00:05:01.030
for the designers, and the
developers, and the PMs,

00:05:01.030 --> 00:05:03.950
and the QA people,
everybody working together,

00:05:03.950 --> 00:05:06.970
because when you have a metaphor
that everybody understands,

00:05:06.970 --> 00:05:08.920
intuitively
understands, you don't

00:05:08.920 --> 00:05:12.550
have to explain how they
violated subsection C, clause

00:05:12.550 --> 00:05:15.110
2 of your style guideline.

00:05:15.110 --> 00:05:16.950
They just know it feels wrong.

00:05:16.950 --> 00:05:18.340
They know it's out of place.

00:05:21.850 --> 00:05:26.290
So why this particular metaphor?

00:05:26.290 --> 00:05:29.450
Why did we imagine
a material that

00:05:29.450 --> 00:05:32.790
was a form of paper
sufficiently advanced

00:05:32.790 --> 00:05:36.560
as to be indistinguishable
from magic?

00:05:36.560 --> 00:05:38.060
Well, one part of
it is of course

00:05:38.060 --> 00:05:42.030
that we do have a
lot of experience

00:05:42.030 --> 00:05:45.750
as humanity
communicating with paper.

00:05:45.750 --> 00:05:54.170
Paper is just rich in a
history across all our cultures

00:05:54.170 --> 00:06:01.000
of conveying information,
and it naturally

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:06.160
affords so many different
ways of interacting with it.

00:06:09.160 --> 00:06:14.190
But the other aspect of paper
is that it is a physical thing.

00:06:14.190 --> 00:06:15.985
It exists in the world.

00:06:18.640 --> 00:06:22.620
And this idea that
surfaces because they

00:06:22.620 --> 00:06:26.920
are tangible are a metaphor
that we can use to accelerate

00:06:26.920 --> 00:06:30.590
understanding of our
UI is really important.

00:06:30.590 --> 00:06:33.660
You have this perception
of objects and surfaces

00:06:33.660 --> 00:06:37.350
that's happening in the more
primitive parts of your brain.

00:06:37.350 --> 00:06:40.390
It's happening in these
visual cortexes that

00:06:40.390 --> 00:06:44.200
are in the back and lower
parts of your brain.

00:06:44.200 --> 00:06:48.840
And that means they're
simply easier than language.

00:06:48.840 --> 00:06:51.390
They are more natural
than language.

00:06:51.390 --> 00:06:53.300
You have this
inherent understanding

00:06:53.300 --> 00:06:57.180
about the separation of things
and the relationships of things

00:06:57.180 --> 00:07:02.740
that allow us to look at
this and have it make sense,

00:07:02.740 --> 00:07:06.870
even though we know there is
no material in the world that

00:07:06.870 --> 00:07:09.030
could possibly do this.

00:07:09.030 --> 00:07:13.950
It is irrational and yet
feels completely natural.

00:07:13.950 --> 00:07:15.500
And that's what
we want when we're

00:07:15.500 --> 00:07:18.140
creating digital,
magical interfaces.

00:07:18.140 --> 00:07:18.640
Right?

00:07:18.640 --> 00:07:21.120
Because we are not
constrained by the laws

00:07:21.120 --> 00:07:23.000
of the real world in
our user interfaces.

00:07:28.880 --> 00:07:31.600
Surfaces are intuitive.

00:07:31.600 --> 00:07:34.220
And that's why we use
them as the foundation.

00:07:34.220 --> 00:07:38.870
They organize space and
rationalize the interaction.

00:07:43.520 --> 00:07:50.560
And it matters that you
preserve this inherent sense

00:07:50.560 --> 00:07:52.260
of what's right.

00:07:52.260 --> 00:07:57.100
Not for the sake of artifice,
but in order to make the mind

00:07:57.100 --> 00:07:58.650
work less.

00:07:58.650 --> 00:08:02.410
One of the things you'll
discover in our material design

00:08:02.410 --> 00:08:08.720
documents is that our buttons
rise to the surface in response

00:08:08.720 --> 00:08:12.080
to touch instead of
syncing into a surface,

00:08:12.080 --> 00:08:17.320
like a fake, plastic
button would.

00:08:17.320 --> 00:08:22.150
And we do this because we want
this illusion to be consistent.

00:08:22.150 --> 00:08:23.980
The idea that when
your finger touches

00:08:23.980 --> 00:08:27.130
that glass on your
phone that surface

00:08:27.130 --> 00:08:29.235
is coming up and
meeting your finger

00:08:29.235 --> 00:08:30.485
at the point where it touches.

00:08:39.179 --> 00:08:42.230
JONATHAN LEE: Content is bold,
graphic, and intentional.

00:08:42.230 --> 00:08:45.200
We pushed ourselves when we were
thinking about material design

00:08:45.200 --> 00:08:50.580
to make clear and deliberate
design decisions regarding

00:08:50.580 --> 00:08:52.990
color and topography.

00:08:52.990 --> 00:08:55.090
So embracing these
classic visual design

00:08:55.090 --> 00:08:57.050
principles Jon and
Matias have both

00:08:57.050 --> 00:09:00.230
spoken about in
our new framework.

00:09:00.230 --> 00:09:02.020
With Ice Cream Sandwich
Android introduced

00:09:02.020 --> 00:09:05.060
a new system font, Roboto.

00:09:05.060 --> 00:09:07.460
And today we're updating
Roboto to go beyond phones

00:09:07.460 --> 00:09:11.912
and tablets, and be the default
typeface for the material UI.

00:09:11.912 --> 00:09:13.870
Here you can see the
current version of Roboto.

00:09:17.030 --> 00:09:19.820
And Roboto is now slightly
rounder, friendlier,

00:09:19.820 --> 00:09:23.379
and most importantly, redrawn to
perform on desktop and beyond.

00:09:23.379 --> 00:09:25.170
And I can tell you from
personal experience

00:09:25.170 --> 00:09:28.050
that it handles really well.

00:09:28.050 --> 00:09:32.850
We also developed and
documented our design guidelines

00:09:32.850 --> 00:09:34.400
for typographic scale.

00:09:34.400 --> 00:09:37.650
By using one typeface and a
handful of weights for emphasis

00:09:37.650 --> 00:09:41.820
we believe that it delivers
consistent and clear

00:09:41.820 --> 00:09:45.080
hierarchies in your products.

00:09:45.080 --> 00:09:47.460
Using scale and
appropriate display sizes

00:09:47.460 --> 00:09:50.290
you can create dynamic,
print like layouts

00:09:50.290 --> 00:09:53.000
with using white
space and contrasts.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:58.110
This focuses your users on the
content that really matters.

00:09:58.110 --> 00:10:01.350
Using vertical key lines
and baseline grids content

00:10:01.350 --> 00:10:05.680
is bold, elegant, and
graphically clear.

00:10:05.680 --> 00:10:07.580
We also developed a
complete color palette

00:10:07.580 --> 00:10:11.430
with intentional color decisions
for shades, tints, and accent

00:10:11.430 --> 00:10:12.200
pops.

00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:14.810
These are not just adding
white and black to a color,

00:10:14.810 --> 00:10:15.681
or using alpha.

00:10:15.681 --> 00:10:17.430
We actually looked at
each of these shades

00:10:17.430 --> 00:10:20.010
and decided what they should be.

00:10:20.010 --> 00:10:22.200
So strong and intelligent
application of color

00:10:22.200 --> 00:10:23.800
gives life to your UIs.

00:10:23.800 --> 00:10:27.030
And it connects users
with your brand.

00:10:27.030 --> 00:10:30.270
It also can create
very strong hierarchy

00:10:30.270 --> 00:10:32.800
and liven up some
pretty standard UIs.

00:10:32.800 --> 00:10:34.580
As you can see in
this example, it's

00:10:34.580 --> 00:10:37.220
essentially some kind of
form that you're filling out.

00:10:37.220 --> 00:10:42.050
And there's a clear
area for your title,

00:10:42.050 --> 00:10:46.270
and that's what we want
people to focus on.

00:10:46.270 --> 00:10:48.470
Dynamic color is
also really exciting.

00:10:48.470 --> 00:10:52.270
Earlier today Matias announced
a new API in the L preview

00:10:52.270 --> 00:10:53.629
called Pallete.

00:10:53.629 --> 00:10:55.670
This system really makes
it easy to color things,

00:10:55.670 --> 00:10:58.175
dynamically select, and
extract color for use.

00:11:00.754 --> 00:11:02.670
One of the things that
you could use color for

00:11:02.670 --> 00:11:04.930
is contrast accent colors.

00:11:04.930 --> 00:11:07.930
Contrast colors make this
floating action button,

00:11:07.930 --> 00:11:10.220
which is the play/pause
button really pop.

00:11:13.340 --> 00:11:15.920
Brand, color, and
icons are accelerators

00:11:15.920 --> 00:11:18.650
that guide users
through your design.

00:11:18.650 --> 00:11:21.277
When think about app icons we
looked at real life studies

00:11:21.277 --> 00:11:22.235
in lighting and shadow.

00:11:24.960 --> 00:11:26.740
We started by defining
a universal grid

00:11:26.740 --> 00:11:30.260
for app icons, one that supports
primary geometric shapes.

00:11:35.690 --> 00:11:38.470
A product icon is the
first literal touch

00:11:38.470 --> 00:11:41.770
point of your user's experience.

00:11:41.770 --> 00:11:44.270
We looked at extracting those
attributes from your icon,

00:11:44.270 --> 00:11:47.130
and from your brand, and
intelligently applying those

00:11:47.130 --> 00:11:49.600
to the surfaces within your UI.

00:11:49.600 --> 00:11:51.620
The top toolbar and the
floating action button,

00:11:51.620 --> 00:11:55.354
again, are accelerators
for those actions.

00:11:55.354 --> 00:11:56.770
Here's just another
example of how

00:11:56.770 --> 00:12:01.990
to connect those services
to the product icon.

00:12:01.990 --> 00:12:05.100
And finally, we took the
same modern, bold, geometric

00:12:05.100 --> 00:12:08.647
approach from app icons and
applied it to the UI icons

00:12:08.647 --> 00:12:09.480
you see in your app.

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:14.180
Our design teams are
now using one common set

00:12:14.180 --> 00:12:18.590
of icons between Android
L, Polymer, and the web.

00:12:18.590 --> 00:12:21.690
This means one trash
can across all devices.

00:12:21.690 --> 00:12:23.940
And we'll be releasing these
icons later this summer

00:12:23.940 --> 00:12:26.180
through our design
guidelines, available for use

00:12:26.180 --> 00:12:27.600
on both Android and the web.

00:12:31.369 --> 00:12:32.660
CHRISTIAN ROBERTSON: All right.

00:12:32.660 --> 00:12:37.740
So even if we're doing all this,
and we've got great typography,

00:12:37.740 --> 00:12:40.700
as an industry we're leveling
up when we start using baseline

00:12:40.700 --> 00:12:43.140
grids, we've got
amazing color, it's

00:12:43.140 --> 00:12:46.590
not enough just to draw the
static states and stop there.

00:12:46.590 --> 00:12:50.300
We can do more to show people
how the states are changing,

00:12:50.300 --> 00:12:53.060
letting them focus on
the content that matters.

00:12:53.060 --> 00:12:55.990
So when you think about it,
almost all state changes

00:12:55.990 --> 00:12:58.470
in the UI start with user input.

00:12:58.470 --> 00:13:02.310
And this is why material
UI puts that user input

00:13:02.310 --> 00:13:04.610
at the center of
the animation story.

00:13:04.610 --> 00:13:06.550
So when I touch the
screen immediately

00:13:06.550 --> 00:13:08.180
the surface responds.

00:13:08.180 --> 00:13:10.040
I can see exactly
where I touched,

00:13:10.040 --> 00:13:13.730
and the intersection of the
object that's responding.

00:13:13.730 --> 00:13:15.160
This does two things.

00:13:15.160 --> 00:13:17.839
First, it tells people
that they've been heard.

00:13:17.839 --> 00:13:18.630
They feel powerful.

00:13:18.630 --> 00:13:20.046
They feel like
they're in control.

00:13:20.046 --> 00:13:21.520
Apps feel responsive.

00:13:21.520 --> 00:13:24.612
Second, it confirms
to them that the UI

00:13:24.612 --> 00:13:26.445
is going to do the thing
that they expected,

00:13:26.445 --> 00:13:28.700
that it's working.

00:13:28.700 --> 00:13:30.240
This animated touch
feedback is now

00:13:30.240 --> 00:13:33.940
built into the platforms for
both Android and Polymer,

00:13:33.940 --> 00:13:38.300
and it's being used by all
of the relevant components.

00:13:41.210 --> 00:13:43.790
So it's not just the
immediate feedback

00:13:43.790 --> 00:13:45.790
though that's centered
on user input.

00:13:45.790 --> 00:13:49.620
The material itself transforms
to bring in new content.

00:13:49.620 --> 00:13:53.360
And all this happens
on a shared stage.

00:13:53.360 --> 00:13:56.890
When I say I shared stage, I'm
talking about the environment

00:13:56.890 --> 00:13:58.720
where this material lives.

00:13:58.720 --> 00:14:01.520
It's important to know as
we're looking at the material

00:14:01.520 --> 00:14:06.340
that it lives in the same scale
and in the same space as we do.

00:14:06.340 --> 00:14:09.060
We're not flying through
some imagined space,

00:14:09.060 --> 00:14:12.240
or looking through a
window into another world.

00:14:12.240 --> 00:14:15.540
This material lives at the same
scale as the device itself,

00:14:15.540 --> 00:14:17.210
whether it's in
our hand, or we're

00:14:17.210 --> 00:14:19.790
looking at it on our desk.

00:14:19.790 --> 00:14:20.810
We don't move.

00:14:20.810 --> 00:14:24.260
The material does to
bring the content to us.

00:14:24.260 --> 00:14:27.240
You can see how this works as
transitions organize themselves

00:14:27.240 --> 00:14:29.530
around the object
as it's selected.

00:14:29.530 --> 00:14:33.920
The material moves, expands
to reveal the new content.

00:14:33.920 --> 00:14:37.530
And notice that even as the
content transforms in a way

00:14:37.530 --> 00:14:40.100
that maybe a physical
material like paper

00:14:40.100 --> 00:14:41.870
wouldn't, it's still
very clear what's

00:14:41.870 --> 00:14:45.117
happening because of the way
the material responds to light,

00:14:45.117 --> 00:14:47.575
and the way the shadows are
being rendered by the platform.

00:14:51.870 --> 00:14:56.510
So animation is crucial to
reinforcing this metaphor

00:14:56.510 --> 00:14:58.210
that Matias talked about.

00:14:58.210 --> 00:15:01.260
It's just in the same
way that shadow rendering

00:15:01.260 --> 00:15:03.060
helps us understand
what we're looking at.

00:15:03.060 --> 00:15:06.410
The way that things move
give cues about how they work

00:15:06.410 --> 00:15:09.280
and about their properties.

00:15:09.280 --> 00:15:14.150
So, for example, the
material animations naturally

00:15:14.150 --> 00:15:16.000
show continuity from
one state to another.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:18.470
When I select an item it
expands to the next state.

00:15:18.470 --> 00:15:19.690
It doesn't jump cut.

00:15:19.690 --> 00:15:21.770
It doesn't blink in and out.

00:15:21.770 --> 00:15:25.330
It moves naturally like
sliding a piece of paper

00:15:25.330 --> 00:15:26.760
across the table.

00:15:26.760 --> 00:15:32.860
If we teleport our users from
one state to another in a UI

00:15:32.860 --> 00:15:34.765
it can be confusing
and disorienting

00:15:34.765 --> 00:15:36.390
when they get to the
other side, almost

00:15:36.390 --> 00:15:40.042
like if we were to be
teleported in the real world.

00:15:40.042 --> 00:15:42.500
If I were to just appear on
the stage in front of everybody

00:15:42.500 --> 00:15:48.430
here, it'd take me a few
moments to get my bearings.

00:15:48.430 --> 00:15:52.180
It's the constraints that are
inherent in the material that

00:15:52.180 --> 00:15:55.990
make it clear for
people what can happen

00:15:55.990 --> 00:16:01.420
and lets them predict and
understand what has happened.

00:16:01.420 --> 00:16:03.700
So if it makes it easier
to understand what's

00:16:03.700 --> 00:16:06.680
changing, at the same time it
can show us what's important.

00:16:06.680 --> 00:16:09.650
So since our eyes are
naturally drawn to motion,

00:16:09.650 --> 00:16:12.190
if something moves, and
it's in our field of view,

00:16:12.190 --> 00:16:13.990
we're going to see it.

00:16:13.990 --> 00:16:19.720
It's a really strong tool
for us to help direct focus.

00:16:19.720 --> 00:16:23.500
If in a music screen
the player controls

00:16:23.500 --> 00:16:27.210
are the primary interaction, the
animation can point that out.

00:16:27.210 --> 00:16:31.200
Also, even noticing the
details, those small things

00:16:31.200 --> 00:16:34.200
that you might not even notice
overtly, like, for example,

00:16:34.200 --> 00:16:41.200
the small slide on the
control slider as it comes in.

00:16:41.200 --> 00:16:42.200
Wait for it.

00:16:42.200 --> 00:16:44.170
There it is.

00:16:44.170 --> 00:16:47.920
Even though people might not
notice it overly, they see it,

00:16:47.920 --> 00:16:49.860
and they know how things
work without having

00:16:49.860 --> 00:16:50.990
to think a lot about it.

00:16:56.120 --> 00:16:58.120
NICHOLAS JITKOF: So these
guys talked about many

00:16:58.120 --> 00:17:00.270
of our core
principles, primarily

00:17:00.270 --> 00:17:01.860
this sense of tangible
surfaces, which

00:17:01.860 --> 00:17:03.485
appeal to the primal
parts of our minds

00:17:03.485 --> 00:17:05.460
with dimension and shading.

00:17:05.460 --> 00:17:07.680
Bold and intentional
design, which provides

00:17:07.680 --> 00:17:09.710
a unified language that
allows brand and UI

00:17:09.710 --> 00:17:11.510
elements to stand out.

00:17:11.510 --> 00:17:12.990
And meaningful
motion, which fuses

00:17:12.990 --> 00:17:15.130
this design and the
surfaces together, and gives

00:17:15.130 --> 00:17:17.665
new affordances and life to UI.

00:17:17.665 --> 00:17:19.869
What we want to use
these for is to create

00:17:19.869 --> 00:17:22.232
a new unified
experience for users.

00:17:22.232 --> 00:17:24.690
We're surrounded by devices,
and people experience our work

00:17:24.690 --> 00:17:26.380
across all of these
different platforms.

00:17:26.380 --> 00:17:28.520
And for that reason we
want to treat every device

00:17:28.520 --> 00:17:30.520
as a window on the same content.

00:17:30.520 --> 00:17:33.210
We want to tailor the form
factor so that each one of them

00:17:33.210 --> 00:17:35.770
has commonalities, but
also can be unique.

00:17:35.770 --> 00:17:37.770
Color, type, and
spatial relationships

00:17:37.770 --> 00:17:39.200
help tie them together.

00:17:39.200 --> 00:17:41.540
In this example
email app the sizes

00:17:41.540 --> 00:17:43.320
are all related by
color and structure,

00:17:43.320 --> 00:17:45.403
but there's diversity in
the overall presentation.

00:17:45.403 --> 00:17:46.590
The larger ones use cards.

00:17:46.590 --> 00:17:48.350
The line length is
kept reasonable.

00:17:48.350 --> 00:17:49.850
And the small ones
end up being full

00:17:49.850 --> 00:17:52.820
bleed so they can take advantage
of the size the device.

00:17:52.820 --> 00:17:55.462
In this file's app there's
a drawer on the side,

00:17:55.462 --> 00:17:57.420
but on desktop it becomes
a persistent element.

00:17:57.420 --> 00:17:59.190
On tablets it's a
temporary overlay

00:17:59.190 --> 00:18:01.990
so it stays out of the
way, and on phones it's

00:18:01.990 --> 00:18:05.094
a persistent UI
that you drill into.

00:18:05.094 --> 00:18:07.760
In this calendar example there's
more variety between the views,

00:18:07.760 --> 00:18:09.885
but, again, typography and
color tie them together.

00:18:09.885 --> 00:18:12.816
So they feel like they're
a consistent experience.

00:18:12.816 --> 00:18:15.560
Immersive imagery also
plays a pretty big role.

00:18:15.560 --> 00:18:17.240
This is something we've seen on
mobile where people are doing

00:18:17.240 --> 00:18:18.170
things full bleed
that we actually

00:18:18.170 --> 00:18:19.775
want to take back to desktop.

00:18:19.775 --> 00:18:21.760
It looks great there as well.

00:18:21.760 --> 00:18:24.480
And in particular, when things
used to be sort of full bleed,

00:18:24.480 --> 00:18:27.234
we now can use things like
cards to keep that same sense,

00:18:27.234 --> 00:18:28.650
even though they're
now surrounded

00:18:28.650 --> 00:18:31.850
by other kinds of content.

00:18:31.850 --> 00:18:33.390
Beyond the platforms
we also care

00:18:33.390 --> 00:18:36.655
about working with
different disciplines.

00:18:36.655 --> 00:18:38.780
Interaction, motion, visual
design, and engineering

00:18:38.780 --> 00:18:40.694
are often not deeply associated.

00:18:40.694 --> 00:18:42.610
And so we've been using
this material metaphor

00:18:42.610 --> 00:18:45.110
as a way to bind the different
disciplines together and make

00:18:45.110 --> 00:18:46.340
them more collaborative.

00:18:46.340 --> 00:18:49.090
In interaction the materials
reinforce the overall sense

00:18:49.090 --> 00:18:49.870
of hierarchy.

00:18:49.870 --> 00:18:51.800
The scrolling and
layering give a good sense

00:18:51.800 --> 00:18:54.430
of how gestures
work, and emphasize

00:18:54.430 --> 00:18:56.900
how the user should
focus their attention.

00:18:56.900 --> 00:18:59.230
Visual design becomes
simpler because of this.

00:18:59.230 --> 00:19:02.619
The content itself can be
very graphic in its hierarchy,

00:19:02.619 --> 00:19:04.410
and rely on dimensionality
for higher level

00:19:04.410 --> 00:19:06.530
structures like toolbars
or other elements

00:19:06.530 --> 00:19:08.930
so they're not
considered together.

00:19:08.930 --> 00:19:12.670
And motion is in most
ways the most important.

00:19:12.670 --> 00:19:14.610
Materiality provides
the grounding for it.

00:19:14.610 --> 00:19:16.380
It makes it consistent
and intuitive.

00:19:16.380 --> 00:19:19.430
So it's obeying
realistic physics,

00:19:19.430 --> 00:19:22.324
and speaking better
to the user for that.

00:19:22.324 --> 00:19:23.740
More importantly,
it allows motion

00:19:23.740 --> 00:19:27.254
to be deeply tied into
interaction and visual design.

