00:29:03.624 --> 00:29:05.040
How to design
gestural interfaces.

00:29:08.030 --> 00:29:14.450
I think a lot of this goes back
to the material as a metaphor.

00:29:14.450 --> 00:29:16.835
And part of what we're
trying to do is-- You know,

00:29:16.835 --> 00:29:21.717
you go and you watch some
summer blockbuster sci-fi movie.

00:29:21.717 --> 00:29:23.800
And sometimes it can be a
little bit of a let down

00:29:23.800 --> 00:29:27.190
because like they set up
the world in which they're

00:29:27.190 --> 00:29:29.520
operating, but then they
break some principle, right?

00:29:29.520 --> 00:29:30.850
And it just kind of falls flat.

00:29:30.850 --> 00:29:32.320
And why did that happen?

00:29:32.320 --> 00:29:35.100
And I think part of what we're
trying to do with a system

00:29:35.100 --> 00:29:40.790
like this is to set up a series
of sort of a world in which it

00:29:40.790 --> 00:29:44.400
functions, and ideally it's
grounded enough in the reality

00:29:44.400 --> 00:29:49.120
that we have here such that you
can bring your intuition of how

00:29:49.120 --> 00:29:53.090
objects function to
the system, and it

00:29:53.090 --> 00:29:56.450
fulfills those expectations,
and hopefully exceeds them,

00:29:56.450 --> 00:29:59.450
but then maybe we add in
additional magical things

00:29:59.450 --> 00:30:01.650
we can't quite do yet
with physical devices

00:30:01.650 --> 00:30:03.700
because we're rendering
with virtual devices.

00:30:03.700 --> 00:30:09.450
The bridging of gesture, and
other types of interfaces to me

00:30:09.450 --> 00:30:12.566
is actually just
another level, it's

00:30:12.566 --> 00:30:13.940
another additional
dimensionality

00:30:13.940 --> 00:30:15.800
in terms of interaction.

00:30:15.800 --> 00:30:16.870
And it's a progression.

00:30:16.870 --> 00:30:18.760
So when we started
with computers

00:30:18.760 --> 00:30:20.590
we basically had keyboard.

00:30:20.590 --> 00:30:22.836
And then eventually
we got a mouse.

00:30:22.836 --> 00:30:24.210
And so that was
like a little bit

00:30:24.210 --> 00:30:25.717
of interaction,
slightly removed.

00:30:25.717 --> 00:30:27.300
You know, here it's
happening up here,

00:30:27.300 --> 00:30:30.010
and I'm using these
things to control it.

00:30:30.010 --> 00:30:31.570
Then we get all the
way now to today

00:30:31.570 --> 00:30:35.154
where we have smartphones
with touch screen displays.

00:30:35.154 --> 00:30:37.070
And now we have this
additional dimensionality

00:30:37.070 --> 00:30:39.740
of being able to physically
touch the software.

00:30:39.740 --> 00:30:42.660
And now we're adding this other
layer in, hopefully over time,

00:30:42.660 --> 00:30:44.310
and hopefully do
it right, where we

00:30:44.310 --> 00:30:47.410
have wearable devices
that have gyros and stuff.

00:30:47.410 --> 00:30:49.160
I mean, even the
cardboard device actually

00:30:49.160 --> 00:30:52.180
is really fascinating because--
Again, it's really awesome.

00:30:52.180 --> 00:30:53.500
You play with it.

00:30:53.500 --> 00:30:55.210
But it's just like
doing, you know,

00:30:55.210 --> 00:30:57.320
basic head tracking
and things like that.

00:30:57.320 --> 00:30:59.140
And so as we continue
to sort of add

00:30:59.140 --> 00:31:05.250
in the dimensionality of
interaction with gestures

00:31:05.250 --> 00:31:08.260
it just makes it
so much more rich.

00:31:08.260 --> 00:31:11.100
And so we just want to make sure
that we're always grounding it

00:31:11.100 --> 00:31:13.470
into sort of these principles
that we set up initially.

00:31:13.470 --> 00:31:14.830
So it's always self consistent.

00:31:14.830 --> 00:31:16.829
You don't get to a moment
where you're like, oh,

00:31:16.829 --> 00:31:18.930
I did this thing, and
that didn't make sense.

00:31:18.930 --> 00:31:22.060
It was discontinuous
with all the principles

00:31:22.060 --> 00:31:24.170
that had been set up before it.

00:31:24.170 --> 00:31:26.980
One of things that I think is
really interesting about this,

00:31:26.980 --> 00:31:29.230
and we'll talk about this
more in tomorrow's sessions,

00:31:29.230 --> 00:31:32.500
is that there's actually
a fair amount of spectrum.

00:31:32.500 --> 00:31:33.430
